<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   22 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> SURINAME </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Liberation Front' Seizes Afobaka Hydroelectric Plant </TI></H3>
<H4>   Threat To Blow Up Dam if President Does Not Resign </H4>
<F P=102> PA2203143194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0812 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2203143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hague, 22 Mar (EFE) -- Surinamese President 
Ronald Venetiaan expressed his willingness to hold a dialogue 
with the rebels who seized a hydroelectric dam and are holding 
30 workers hostage, the Dutch agency ANP reported from 
Paramaribo today. 
  On 21 March, 100 guerrillas of the self-styled Liberation 
Front of Suriname seized the Afobaka Dam, located 100 km south 
of Paramaribo, and mined its main access roads. 
  The rebel group is holding 30 workers of the Suralco mining 
company hostage and threatening to blow up the dam at 1400 today 
Dutch time (1300 GMT), leaving Paramaribo without electricity, 
if the government does not resign. 
  In addition to President Venetiaan's resignation, the Front 
demands a broad program to improve "the critical economic 
situation" as well as health and education services for the 
population. 
  The group is also asking for the withdrawal of a Canadian 
company that extracts gold in various concessions in the 
interior of the country and that the mining rights be granted to 
Surinamers. 
  In an appeal to the population, Venetiaan asked for a 
dialogue with the rebels to reach a peaceful solution to the 
conflict, ANP revealed from the former Dutch colony in northern 
South America. 
  The president added, however, that violence does not solve 
anything and that "terrorism will never force me to resign." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

