<F P=101> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Conscript, Civilian Executed for Attempted Sabotage </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2003180694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1740 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2003180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 20 Mar (MENA) -- A military judicial source 
stated that army conscript Midhat 'Abd-al-'Al Bayyumi and 
civilian Muhammad Ahmad Muhammad Sa'id were executed today. The 
Higher Military Court had unanimously sentenced them, together 
with a third fugitive defendant named Hamadah Muhammad Lutfi, to 
death in case no. 94/2 of the Military Prosecution Office. 
  The source said that the military prosecution accused the 
two 
civilians, who belonged to the al-Jihad Organization, of seizing 
the opportunity to recruit the conscript in the Armed Forces and 
agreed to provide him with some explosives to use for 
sabotaging one of the military installations in his unit. 
  The source added that the two civilians did in fact bring 
the 
explosives to the conscript but the latter was arrested and the 
explosives seized before the operation was carried out. One of 
his partners was also arrested while the third remains a 
fugitive. 
  The source noted that the court sentenced the three to death 
after being defended by four lawyers. He said that the 
sentences were ratified and then the defendants appealed the 
sentences. The appeals were turned down and legally rejected 
and, therefore, the sentences became final and due for 
implementation. 
  It is recalled that some foreign radios and news agencies 
had 
given an inaccurate report on this issue. 

</TEXT>

